ce:section.ce:para:
At present, there are countless studies on the synthesis of CDs from biomass by different methods, and the corresponding fluorescence quantum yield are also different. Among them, only four articles have improved the fluorescence quantum yield of CDs prepared by hydrothermal method to more than 35 % [26]. In order to make a more comprehensive comparison of the QY of ESCQDs obtained in this article, 30 biomass/waste CDs [12,27–55] synthesized using hydrothermal methods and corresponding emission wavelength were analyzed in this study (Fig. 4(e) and 
                        Table 2). Among the total 30 CDs, most of them had QYs between 5 % and 17 %, and ESCQDs synthesized in this study exceed the majority of the biomass/waste-derived CDs. CDs synthesized from wool and pig hair were reported with the higher QY (26 %), which may be attributed to the high hydrothermal temperature (240
                           ℃
                        ) and sulfur-nitrogen co-doping formation during the synthesis process [28] (Table 2). QYs of rice residues-derived CDs were up to 23.48 %, the corresponding hydrothermal temperature (200
                           ℃
                        ) was same as the conditions in our study. However, lysine was added to promote the nitrogen doping formation and improve the fluorescence property [27] (Table 2). Feng et al. synthesized graphene quantum dots under the catalysis of H2O2 using sewage sludge as a precursor, and its QY was 10.3 % without the observation of doping formation [12]. Comparatively, the synthesis process in our study does not use catalysts or add exogenous reactants. The synthesis temperature was relatively low, which reduces the energy consumption over the reaction. The resulted ESCQDs are competitive with high QY, demonstrating the superiority of excess sludge for the synthesis of CQDs. Moreover, compared with most nitrogen-doped CDs, the ESCQDs formed calcium-nitrogen co-doping, which may support its high QY.
